<BlogPostLayout
  title="How to Light a Wood Heater (and What to Do When It Won't Draw)"
  description="Step-by-step guide to lighting a wood heater or slow combustion heater properly — plus how to fix the most common problems when it won't light or won't draw."
  publishDate="April 2026"
  readTime="7 min"
>

  <p>Every year at the start of winter, the same thing happens across Melbourne: someone tries to light their wood heater for the first time in months, something goes wrong, and they end up with a room full of smoke or a fire that won't stay alight.</p>

  <p>If that's you right now — or you want to avoid it — here's exactly how to light a wood heater properly, and what to do when it isn't working.</p>

  <h2>What You Need Before You Start</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.65rem;margin:1.1rem 0 1.4rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;background:#f5f0e8;border-radius:10px;padding:.9rem 1rem;">
      <span style="font-size:1.3rem;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">🪵</span>
      <div><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Dry, seasoned firewood</strong><br/><span style="font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;">This is the most important factor. Seasoned hardwood has been dried for at least 12 months. Knock two pieces together — a sharp crack means dry, a dull thud means too wet.</span></div>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;background:#f5f0e8;border-radius:10px;padding:.9rem 1rem;">
      <span style="font-size:1.3rem;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">🔥</span>
      <div><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Dry kindling</strong><br/><span style="font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;">Small dry sticks or commercial kindling. Skimping on kindling is one of the most common reasons fires fail to get going.</span></div>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.75rem;background:#f5f0e8;border-radius:10px;padding:.9rem 1rem;">
      <span style="font-size:1.3rem;line-height:1;flex-shrink:0;">📰</span>
      <div><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Fire starters or newspaper</strong><br/><span style="font-size:.95rem;color:#5a5a54;">Waxy fire starters are most reliable. Never use petrol, metho or lighter fluid in a wood heater.</span></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Step-by-Step: How to Light a Wood Heater</h2>

  <!-- Step 1 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">1</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Open the air controls fully</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Before anything else, fully open all air vents on the heater — primary and secondary. This gives the fire maximum oxygen to establish itself.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 2 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">2</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Check the damper is open</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">If your heater or fireplace has a damper, make sure it's fully open before lighting. A closed damper is one of the most common causes of a room full of smoke.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 3 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">3</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Prime the flue (cold mornings — don't skip this)</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">If the heater hasn't been used for weeks, the air inside the flue is cold and dense — it wants to fall down into the room. Light a rolled newspaper and hold it inside the heater near the flue opening for 30–60 seconds. You'll feel the draw establish as warm air starts pulling upward. Once you feel that suction, you're ready.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>Cold flue downdraught is the most common cause of smoke in the room on the first fire of the season. Priming takes 60 seconds and prevents the problem entirely.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 4 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">4</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Build the fire — top-down method</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Place two or three larger logs on the bottom of the firebox. Stack kindling in a crisscross pattern on top. Place fire starters or scrunched newspaper on top of the kindling. Light from the top. The fire burns downward, generating heat rapidly and establishing draw before the big logs catch.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 5 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">5</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Leave the door slightly ajar for the first few minutes</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">On most slow combustion heaters, cracking the door open while the fire establishes helps airflow. Check your heater's manual — some manufacturers recommend this, others don't.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 6 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">6</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Add larger logs once kindling is burning well</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Don't rush it. Wait until you have a strong bed of flame before loading hardwood. Add one or two pieces at a time — don't overload the firebox.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 7 -->
  <div style="display:flex;gap:.9rem;align-items:flex-start;margin:1.1rem 0 1.6rem;">
    <div style="background:#c8500a;color:#fff;font-size:1rem;font-weight:800;width:2rem;height:2rem;border-radius:50%;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">7</div>
    <div>
      <strong style="color:#1a1a18;font-size:1.05rem;">Adjust the air controls down</strong>
      <p style="margin:.3rem 0 0;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Once the fire is clearly going and you've added your first hardwood load, gradually reduce the air controls to slow the burn rate and improve efficiency. Don't close them down too fast — let the fire settle first.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Work photo -->
  <div style="margin:1.5rem 0;text-align:center;">
    <img
      src="/images/work2.png"
      alt="Professional wood heater flue cleaning Melbourne"
      style="width:100%;max-width:560px;height:auto;border-radius:12px;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;"
