  <h2>Common Problems and How to Fix Them</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.75rem;margin:1.1rem 0 1.4rem;">

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        🚫 The fire won't stay alight
        <span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#c8500a;flex-shrink:0;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Almost always a firewood problem. Wet wood won't sustain combustion no matter how well you build the fire. Check your wood — it should feel light for its size, have visible end cracks, and make a sharp sound when knocked together. Use more kindling and fire starters short-term, but get properly seasoned wood sorted.</div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        💨 Smoke is coming back into the room
        <span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#c8500a;flex-shrink:0;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Work through these in order: (1) Check the damper is open. (2) Prime the flue with a lit newspaper — cold downdraught is the most common cause. (3) Open air controls fully. (4) Crack a window slightly — if draw improves, the house is too tightly sealed. (5) If none of the above works, the flue is blocked or heavily sooted and needs a professional clean.</div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        📉 Fire lights but keeps dying down
        <span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#c8500a;flex-shrink:0;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">The flue isn't drawing strongly enough. Open the heater door briefly — if the fire picks up immediately, restricted airflow is the issue. Causes: dirty flue, partial blockage, or the house being too airtight. Try cracking a window first. If it doesn't help, book a flue clean.</div>
    </details>

    <details style="background:#f5f0e8;border:1px solid #e2ddd4;border-radius:10px;padding:0;overflow:hidden;">
      <summary style="padding:.9rem 1rem;font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#1a1a18;cursor:pointer;list-style:none;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;">
        🌡️ Heater gets hot but room stays cold
        <span style="font-size:1.2rem;color:#c8500a;flex-shrink:0;">+</span>
      </summary>
      <div style="padding:.1rem 1rem 1rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.65;">Air controls are probably too open — the fire is burning through wood fast without radiating heat. Reduce them gradually once the fire is established. Also check for draughts or poorly sealed windows letting the heat escape.</div>
    </details>

  </div>

  <h2>When the Problem Is the Flue, Not the Fire</h2>

  <p>If you've worked through everything — dry wood, primed flue, air controls open, damper open, tried cracking a window — and you're still getting smoke or the fire won't establish, the flue is almost certainly the issue.</p>

  <p>The two most common flue problems:</p>

  <p><strong>Creosote and soot buildup.</strong> After a season of use, the inside of the flue can be heavily coated. This narrows the effective opening, restricts airflow and kills draw. A heater that worked fine at the end of last winter can deteriorate enough over summer that it struggles this year.</p>

  <p><strong>Bird nest or blockage.</strong> Unused chimneys are prime nesting spots over spring and summer. Signs: scratching sounds from the flue earlier in the year, twigs falling into the firebox, or sudden severe smoke spillage on the first fire of the season. Don't try to burn through it — get it professionally cleared.</p>

