  <h2>How to Keep It Running Well All Winter</h2>

  <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.55rem;margin:1rem 0 1.4rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.7rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-weight:800;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">✓</span>
      <span><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Only burn dry seasoned hardwood.</strong> Red gum, ironbark, messmate and stringybark are Melbourne's best options. Store it undercover with airflow.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.7rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-weight:800;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">✓</span>
      <span><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Don't smoulder the fire overnight.</strong> Running the heater very slowly with restricted air produces a lot of creosote. Load with good hardwood and reduce air gradually rather than closing it right down.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.7rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-weight:800;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">✓</span>
      <span><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Watch the glass.</strong> Black glass means incomplete combustion — usually wet wood or too little air. Clean glass means efficient burning.</span>
    </div>
    <div style="display:flex;align-items:flex-start;gap:.7rem;font-size:.97rem;color:#5a5a54;line-height:1.6;">
      <span style="color:#c8500a;font-weight:800;flex-shrink:0;margin-top:.1rem;">✓</span>
      <span><strong style="color:#1a1a18;">Get the flue cleaned annually.</strong> Once a year before the heating season — ideally April or May. Required under most home insurance policies and the single best thing you can do for heater performance and safety.</span>
    </div>
  </div>

